According to the annual Health Bulletin of the Belize Bureau of Statistics, death rates among Belizean men matching a similar demographic to Ortiz shows that men lose their lives to hypertension, heart diseases, cancer, and diabetes at a rate almost double compared to women.

Data also shows that the leading causes of death for Belizean men over 30 are to conditions caused by high blood pressure, cancer, and non-AIDS related immuno-deficiency syndrome, or HIV.

Nevers says gender roles are another chief factor for why men aren’t taking proper responsibility of their health needs in Belize.

Nevers said that locally, females tend to be more aware of their health and well-being, and more often than not, make or encourage husbands, partners or children to visit the clinic for health visits.

However, Nevers blamed this unfortunate lack of healthy habits among Belizean men and informed the audience of a growing trend of “chronic diseases plaguing the government’s healthcare system.”

A growing number of Belizeans over the age of 50 are falling prey to chronic heart ailments and high blood pressure conditions.

Director of the Directorate for Health Services Dr. Marvin Manzanero told The Reporter in 2014 that there was no specific plan to combat the alarming increase of heart disease among Belizeans, though they have been tracking its increase “quite closely.”
